        <body>
            <div type="glosses">
                <note xml:id="PASSTHEALPSGLOSS" resp="#DCH">&#x201C;To day we pass the Alps&#x201D; (MS IA, <hi rend="italic">g</hi>.2; <hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> [1891]; <hi rend="italic">Works</hi> [1903])&#x2014;The 
                    Ruskin family approached the <geogName corresp="#ALPS">Alps</geogName> 
                    for the first time from the north, traveling from <placeName corresp="#SCHAFFHAUSEN">Schaffhausen</placeName> and <placeName corresp="#CONSTANCE">Constance</placeName>, 
                    and they crossed into <placeName corresp="#ITALY">Italy</placeName> through the <geogName corresp="#VIAMALA">Via Mala</geogName> and the <geogName corresp="#SPLUGEN">Spl&#x00FC;gen Pass</geogName> 
                    (see <ref type="note" subtype="contextual" target="tour_of_1833_note.php">Tour of 1833</ref>).<lb/>
                    
                    To describe the approach and crossing, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> intended, according to his <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_toc_msviii.php">Plan for Continuation of the Account of a Tour on the Continent</ref>, 
                    to situate <ref type="witness" target="passing_the_alps_poem_msia_g2.php">&#x201C;Passing the Alps&#x201D;</ref> 
                    at the start of a cluster of poems and/or prose pieces about the experience of crossing the <geogName corresp="#ALPS">Alps</geogName>, several of which he did draft in verse: <ref type="witness" target="passing_the_alps_poem_msia_g2.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRPASSINGTHEALPSPOEM">Passing the Alps</title>&#x201D;</ref>, 
                    <ref type="witness" target="viamala_poem_msviii.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRVIAMALA">Via Mala</title>&#x201D;</ref>, 
                    <ref type="witness" target="splugen_poem_msviii.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRSPLUGEN">Splugen</title>&#x201D;</ref>, <ref type="witness" target="the_summit_poem_msviii.php">&#x201C;The Summit&#x201D;</ref>, 
                    <ref type="witness" target="the_descent_poem_msviii.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHEDESCENT">The Descent</title>&#x201D;</ref>, and &#x201C;<title type="composition" corresp="#JRITALIACOMP">Italia, Italia</title>&#x201D;.<!-- DCH: "Italia, Italia" has only a title tag; no witness exists for this poem --> 
                    As sections leading up to <ref type="witness" target="passing_the_alps_poem_msia_g2.php">&#x201C;<title type ="composite" corresp="#JRPASSINGTHEALPSCOMP">Passing the Alps</title>&#x201D;</ref>, 
                    the plan lists <ref type="witness" target="schaffhausen_poem_msviii.php">&#x201C;Schaffhausen&#x201D;</ref>, 
                    &#x201C;<title type ="composite" corresp="#JRTHEALPSCOMP">The Alps</title>&#x201D;, &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRTHEFALLOFTHERHINECOMP">The Fall of the Rhine</title>&#x201D;, &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRCONSTANCECOMP">Constance</title>&#x201D;, &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRWERDENBERGCOMP">Werdenberg</title>&#x201D;,and &#x201C;<tite type="composite" corresp="#JRPFAFFERSCOMP">Pfaffers</tite>&#x201D;.<lb/><!-- DCH: again, apart from Schaffhausen, title tags only; no witnesses for these poems exist -->
                    
                    <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> models this arrangement on <hi rend="italic">Italy</hi> by <ref type="note" subtype="biographical" target="rogers_samuel_note.php">Samuel Rogers (<date notBefore="1763" notAfter="1855">1763&#x2013;1855</date>)</ref>, 
                    in which a poem about the western Alpine pass, &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRTHEGRANDSTBERNARDCOMP">The Great St. Bernard</title>&#x201D;, gives way to &#x201C;<title type ="composite" corresp="#JRTHEDESCENTCOMP">The Descent</title>&#x201D;, 
                    followed by &#x201C;The Alps&#x201D;. In the latter poem, <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName>&#x02BC;s speaker retraces imaginatively the entire span of the crossing, 
                    preparing for his celebration of arrival in the following poems about <placeName corresp="#ITALY">Italy</placeName>. 
                    (Also, between &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRTHEDESCENTCOMP">The Descent</title>&#x201D; and &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="JRTHEALPSCOMP">The Alps</title>&#x201D;, <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName> pauses to relate two verse tales: &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#ROGERSJORASSE">Jorasse</title>&#x201D;, 
                    a highland tale about an intrepid Alpine hunter; and &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#ROGERSMARGUERITEDETOURS">Marguerite de Tours</title>&#x201D;, a lowland tale about a girl who crosses from <placeName corresp="MARTIGNY">Martigny</placeName>, 
                    on the Swiss side of the <geogName corresp="#STBERNARD">St. Bernard</geogName>, to the opposite <placeName corresp="#VALDAOSTA">vale of Aosta</placeName> in order to attend to her dying father. 
                    In the <date when="1839">1839</date> edition, <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName> added a third tale, &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#ROGERSTHEBROTHERS">The Brothers</title>&#x201D;, about twin brothers who lose their infant brother to an eagle.)<lb/>
                    
                    In <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_toc_msviii.php">plan</ref> for the &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRACCOUNTTOUR">Account</title>&#x201D;,<!-- There is not title type for this tag in the crib sheet.--> 
                    he makes <ref type="witness" target="passing_the_alps_poem_msia_g2.php">&#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRPASSINGTHEALPSCOMP">Passing the Alps</title>&#x201D;</ref> serve the structural function of <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName>&#x02BC;s 
                    &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#ROGERSTHEALPS">The Alps</title>&#x201D; as a summary reflection on the experience of crossing. Both poems use a trope of the <geogName corresp="#ALPS">Alps</geogName> as a &#x201C;barrier&#x201D; between civilizations, 
                    a trope developed by a historical reference to <persName corresp="#HANNIBAL">Hannibal</persName> as the sublime analogy for struggling against that barrier 
                    (<persName corresp="#HANNIBAL">Hannibal</persName>&#x02BC;s crossing is also the subject of <persName corresp="#JMWT">Turner</persName>&#x02BC;s vignette for &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#ROGERSTHEALPS">The Alps</title>&#x201D; 
                    in the <date when="1830">1830</date> illustrated <hi rend="italic"><title type="composite" corresp="#JRITALYCOMP">Italy</title></hi>). Thus, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> captures <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName>&#x02BC;s 
                    idea of one poem serving as an epitome of the experience of crossing that is elaborated&#x2014;topographically, historically, anecdotally&#x2014;in surrounding poems.<lb/>
                    
                    There are also differences between <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s 
                    and <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName>&#x02BC;s crossing poems. In <ref type="witness" target="passing_the_alps_poem_msia_g2.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRPASSINGTHEALPSPOEM">Passing the Alps</title>&#x201D;</ref>, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> 
                    develops the vision of <persName corresp="#HANNIBAL">Hannibal</persName>&#x02BC;s invasion as its sole topic, 
                    whereas in &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#ROGERSTHEALPS">The Alps</title>&#x201D; <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName> characteristically contrasts the turbulent past with his speaker&#x02BC;s present 
                    &#x201C;path of pleasure&#x201D; (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#ROGERSITALY1830">Rogers, <hi rend="italic"><title type="book" corresp="#ROGERSITALY1830">Italy</title></hi> [1830]</ref>, 30). 
                    Also, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, according to his <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_toc_msviii.php">plan</ref>, 
                    intended to situate <ref type="witness" target="passing_the_alps_poem_msia_g2.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRPASSINGTHEALPSPOEM">Passing the Alps</title>&#x201D;</ref> 
                    at the head of a cluster of poems about the mountain pass, unlike <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName> who posed &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#ROGERSTHEALPS">The Alps</title>&#x201D; as a retrospection past the watershed. 
                    Despite these differences, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> clearly adopted structural cues from <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName>&#x02BC;s sequence of poems.<lb/>
                    
                    According to this interpretation, <persName corresp="#WGC">W. G. Collingwood</persName> violated <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s structural intentions. 
                    As the first editor to reconstruct the &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRACCOUNTTOUR">Account</title>&#x201D; by appending draft to <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s 
                    <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_msix.php"><title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIX">MS IX</title> fair copy</ref>, <persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName> erred 
                    by placing &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="##JRPASSINGTHEALPSPOEM">Passing the Alps</title>&#x201D; between <ref type="witness" target="genoa_poem_1891.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRGENOA">Genoa</title>&#x201D;</ref> 
                    and <ref type="witness" target="chamouni_poem_msvii.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRCHAMOUNI">Chamouni</title>&#x201D;</ref>, causing <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s poem 
                    to function as a transition between <placeName corresp="#ITALY">Italy</placeName> and <placeName corresp="#SWITZERLAND">Switzerland</placeName>, 
                    rather than between <placeName corresp="#GERMANY">Germany</placeName> and <placeName corresp="#ITALY">Italy</placeName>. The latter arrangement appears to have been in 
                    <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s mind as early as the <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_msia_g2.php"><title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIA">MS IA</title>, <hi rend="italic">g</hi>.2</ref> sequence, 
                    which pairs <ref type="witness" target="passing_the_alps_poem_msia_g2.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRPASSINGTHEALPSPOEM">Passing the Alps</title>&#x201D;</ref> with 
                    <ref type="witness" target="milan_cathedral_poem_msia_g2.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRMILANCATHEDRAL">Milan Cathedral</title>&#x201D;</ref>.<lb/>
                    
                    In another view, however, <persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName>&#x02BC;s erroneous placement of &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRPASSINGTHEALPSPOEM">Passing the Alps</title>&#x201D; was inspired, 
                    for while he disrupted <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s elaboration of <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName>&#x02BC;s model, 
                    the editor used available materials to patch together an approximation of how <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s cluster of poems 
                    about the north crossing would eventually have been mirrored by a cluster about the western crossing. According to <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s 
                    <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_toc_msviii.php">plan</ref>, the <geogName corresp="#SPLUGEN">Spl&#x00FC;gen</geogName> cluster, extending from 
                    <ref type="witness" target="passing_the_alps_poem_msia_g2.php">&#x201C;<titlt type="poem" corresp="#JRPASSINGTHEALPSPOEM">Passing the Alps</titlt>&#x201D;</ref> through 
                    <ref type="witness" target="the_descent_poem_msviii.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHEDESCENT">The Descent</title>&#x201D;</ref> and poems on the Italian lakes, 
                    would have been mirrored in reverse by a cluster including &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRTHEASCENTCOMP">The Ascent</title>&#x201D; and &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRTHEGRANDSTBERNARDCOMP">The Grand St. Bernard</title>&#x201D;, leading to &#x201C;<title type="poem" corresl="#JRTHELAKEOFGENEVACOMP">The Lake of Geneva</title>&#x201D;&#x2014;and 
                    doubtless this cluster, too, would have exploited <persName corresp="#SR">Rogers</persName>&#x02BC;s tropes about crossings. Thus, <persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName>&#x02BC;s 
                    solution reveals another way in which <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> abandoned &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRACCOUNT"> The Account</title>&#x201D; only when he had effectively completed his apprenticeship to his models 
                    (see <ref type="apparatus" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent.php#SOURCES">Account of a Tour on the Continent: Discussion&#x2014;Sources</ref>). 
                    Moreover, <persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName>&#x02BC;s &#x201C;misplacement&#x201D; allows <ref type="witness" target="passing_the_alps_poem_msia_g2.php">&#x201C;<title type="poem" corresp="#JRPASSINGTHEALPSPOEM">Passing the Alps</title>&#x201D;</ref> 
                    to stand in for &#x201C;<title type="composite" corresp="#JRTHEGRANDSTBERNARDCOMP">The Grand St. Bernard</title>&#x201D;, which <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> never composed, by associating the reference to 
                    <persName corresp="#HANNIBAL">Hannibal</persName>&#x02BC;s crossing with a western passage where the event belongs historically.</note>
                
                <note xml:id="BARRIERGLOSS" resp="#DCH">&#x201C;The barrier of boundless length&#x201D; (MS IA, <hi rend="italic">g</hi>.2; <hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> [1891]; <hi rend="italic">Works</hi> [1903])&#x2014;Cf. &#x201C;To me they [the <placeName corresp="ALPS">Alps</placeName>] seemed the barriers of a world&#x201D; 
                    (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#ROGERSITALY1830">Rogers, <hi rend="italic">Italy</hi> (1830)</ref>, 30).</note>
                
                <note xml:id="QUEENOFNATIONSGLOSS" resp="#DCH">&#x201C;The Queen of nations&#x201D; (MS IA, <hi rend="italic">g</hi>.2; <hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> [1891]; <hi rend="italic">Works</hi> [1903])&#x2014;<placeName corresp="#ROMEANCIENT">Ancient Rome</placeName>.</note>
                
                <note xml:id="CARTHAGINIANFOEGLOSS" resp="#DCH">&#x201C;The Carthaginian foe . . . Avalanches roar&#x201D; (MS IA, <hi rend="italic">g</hi>.2; <hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> [1891]; <hi rend="italic">Works</hi> [1903])&#x2014;In <date when="-0218">218 BC</date>, 
                    near the start of the <date notBefore="-0218" notAfter="-0201">Second Punic War</date> between <placeName corresp="#CARTHAGEANCIENT">Carthage</placeName> and <placeName corresp="#ROMEANCIENT">Rome</placeName>, 
                    the Carthaginian leader, <persName corresp="#HANNIBAL">Hannibal</persName>, led his army on an unprecedented march across the <geogName corresp="#ALPS">Alps</geogName>, 
                    invading <placeName corresp="#ITALY">Italy</placeName> and surprising <placeName corresp="#ROMEANCIENT">Rome</placeName> via a western passage somewhere in present&#x2010;day 
                    <placeName corresp="#PIEDMONT">Piedmont</placeName>.</note>
                
                <note xml:id="CANNAESPLAINGLOSS" resp="#DCH">&#x201C;<placeName corresp="#CANNAE">Cann&#230;</placeName>s plain&#x201D; (MS IA, <hi rend="italic">g</hi>.2; <hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> [1891]; <hi rend="italic">Works</hi> [1903])&#x2014;An area in <placeName corresp="#APULIA">Apulia</placeName>, 
                    in southeast <placeName corresp="#ITALY">Italy</placeName>, where <persName corresp="#HANNIBAL">Hannibal</persName>&#x02BC;s 
                    army won a major victory over a large Roman force in <date when="-0216">216 BC</date>.</note>
            </div>
